06968nam a22009135i 9780824847715DE-B159720220729113935.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220729t20142014hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248477157 a10.1515/97808248477152doi  a(DE-B1597)488098  a(OCoLC)1024055516  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aCRA0400002bisacsh04a746.420996922300a‘Ike Ulana Lau Hala :bThe Vitality and Vibrancy of Lau Hala Weaving Traditions in Hawai‘i /ced. by Marsha MacDowell, C. Kurt Dewhurst, Lia O’Neill M. A. Keawe, Maenette K. P. Ah Nee Benham. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (156 p.) :b38 b&w images, 5 color plates  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aHawai'i Studies on Korea00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tFrom the Dean -- tEditors’ Note -- tA Note on the Cover Art -- tKa Mele No Ka Ulu Lauhala O Kona -- tAloha Ka Lau Pūhala -- tKa Ulana Kaulana -- t‘Ike Pāpale: Lau Hala in Hawaiian Cultural Heritage -- tHarvesting Lau Hala in The Bernice Pauahi Bishop Museum’s Photograph Collection -- tHe Momi Waiwai Ko Kākou Mau Kūpuna -- tKa Ulana Moena Pāwehe -- tThe Past and Future of Hala (Pandanus tectorius) in Hawai‘i -- tA Conversation with Uncle Roy L. Benham -- tThe Lauhala Mat -- tContributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe weaving of lau hala represents a living tradition borne on the great arc of Pacific voyaging history. This thriving tradition is made immediate by masters of the art who transmit their knowledge to those who are similarly devoted to, and delighted by, the smoothness, softness, and that particular warm fragrance of a woven lau hala treasure. The third volume in the Hawai‘inuiākea series, ‘Ike Ulana Lau Hala is an intriguing collection of articles and images about the Hawaiian tradition of ulana lau hala: the weaving, by hand, of dried Pandanus tectorius leaves.‘Ike Ulana Lau Hala considers the humble hala leaf through several, very different lenses: an analysis of lau hala items that occur in historic photographs from the Bishop Museum collections; the ecological history on hala in Hawai‘i and the Pacific including serious challenges to its survival and strategies to prevent its extinction; perspectives–in Hawaiian–of a native speaker from Ni‘ihau on master weavers and the relationship between teacher and learner; a review–also in Hawaiian– of references to lau hala in poetical sayings and idioms; a survey of lau hala in Hawaiian cultural heritage and the documentation project underway to share the art with a broader audience; and a conversation with a master artisan known for his distinct and intricate construction of the lei hala. Rich with imagery, this extraordinary volume will guide the reader to a better understanding of the cultural scope and importance of lau hala, fostering an appreciation of the level of excellence to which the art of ulana lau hala has risen under the guidance of masters who continue to steer the Hawaiian form of the tradition into the future.Contributors include: Lia Keawe, Marsha MacDowell, Kurt Dewhurst, Marques Marzan, Jenna Robinson, Betty Kam, Annette Ku‘uipolani Wong, Kekeha Solis, Timothy Gallaher, and Kaiwipuni Lipe with Uncle Roy Benham. The volume is co-edited by Keawe, MacDowell, and Dewhurst.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aHala tree -- Utilization -- Hawaii. 0aLauhala weaving -- Hawaii. 7aCRAFTS & HOBBIES / Weaving.2bisacsh1 aBenham, Maenette K. P. Ah Nee, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDewhurst, C. Kurt, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDewhurst, C. Kurt, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGallaher, Timothy, econtributor.4c